Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["13. Notes on FFT Conventions", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"ae703886-f288-4fb7-b47c-80521eddd21a"],

Cell["\<\
FFT convention mapping (NumPy \[LeftRightArrow] Mathematica):

  NumPy:  np.fft.ifft2(X)  with default FourierParameters
  Mathematica:  InverseFourier[X, FourierParameters -> {1, -1}]

The FourierParameters -> {1, -1} gives the physics convention:
  InverseFourier: (1/N) \[CapitalSigma] X_k exp(+2\[Pi]ikn/N)

fftshift/ifftshift: For even N, both are equivalent to
  RotateLeft[data, {N/2, N/2}]

Grid correspondence:
  k-space:  k_n = (n - N/2) dk,    dk = 2 kmax / N
  x-space:  x_m = (m - N/2) dx,    dx = \[Pi] / kmax
  Spatial period: L = N \[Pi] / kmax

Key differences from Python:
  \[Bullet] Mathematica indices are 1-based (center at N/2 + 1)
  \[Bullet] KroneckerDelta[i,j] is built-in
  \[Bullet] Sqrt automatically handles complex branch cuts
  \[Bullet] Associations (<|...|>) used instead of Python dicts\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8f975d00-25c3-4cbd-ad8b-c23d043f51df"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
